e fractures. Universities offer a fascinating lens on what society considers important. Not only should we consider the role of the university in every society, we should consider how that role has instantiated itself over many generations, and even over nearly one millennium. The extent to which the modern university is medieval offers, the author suggests, both cause for hope and cause for concern.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEducation, HigherxPhilosophy. 0aMedievalism. 0aUniversities and collegesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aConvocation.  aCurriculum.  aMedievalism.  aPresident.  aUniversity Governance.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066284940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781942401186zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781942401186423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781942401186/original  a978-3-11-066284-9  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK